Caleb Perry - Pluck n' Drop - 9/18/2018

How to run:
Wanna break you computer's think rock? Run the whole test with:

~$ sh run.sh

Otherwise, just run the first test with:

~$ python3 pluck.py test_files/test1.txt

Methodology:
* Basic break down:
My algorithm is a localized random search function that is kind of different due to
the way it reacts to fitness after taking steps. My algorithm takes a big step, and 
then a bunch of small steps within that step in order to nail down the best fitness
for each "chunk". The algorithm has four chunks that it creates and tests fitness for.
In order to judge a randomly generated chunks fitness, it is concatenated with the
chunks decided on prior and ran as normal. The chunk with the lowest fitness wins
and it then subsequently used to decide the next chunk and so on.

* Deciding Chunk size:
Chunk size was decided by using a graph function you can view here ( https://www.desmos.com/calculator/snls1lpu4w )
This function was derived by analyzing the values returned from the deterministic function. It was improtant
to use the operation strings that were not optimized as those had been tampered with and therefore have less
commonality with the operation strings that would later come out of the LRS function. By using this data, I was
able to plot out points as a relation described as (# OF COLUMNS, OPERATIONS EXECUTED ON THE STACK)**. From there
I plotted a best fit line and derived a slop to use for my own function as well as a multiplier to use that would
allow room for outlier operation counts that could potentially lead to some nice fitness scores.

** Note: A stack execution is exclusively defined as a pluck and subsequent drop. Movements dont constitute executions.

* When did restarting occur:
because chunking was implemented and iterations split evenly between the chunks, restarting wasn't necessary as
a bad chunk wouldn't be selected if it were to created an unfavorable fitness and run the whole operation strings
off the rails too much. Having said that, some rare occurances to appear where fitness between chunks goes from the
thousands back down to sub 200 (in test1).

* How randomness was created:
Randomness is achieved by randomly generating the domino type int lists we talked about in class.
This was done with python's "random" library (specifically, random.randint()).

*** HOW TO IMPROVE FROM HERE ***
My results overall were pretty bad but they did come fairly quickly. A compromise between performance and computation
time can definitely be made that will result in better results. This can be obtained by increasing the chunk
count, allowing for more stack executions (this is the big one as far as im concerned), and perhaps adding more 
randomness if the algorithm finds that it's starting out on a bad foot (re-seed and restart, or flip 'dominos' around).
